  "text": "anchor Image credit: GION The Fukutake Foundation has opened the Tadao Ando-designed Naoshima New Museum of Art in Japan. The museum is the latest addition to the Benesse Art Site Naoshima, a decades-long cultural initiative integrating art, architecture, and nature across the islands of Naoshima, Teshima, and Inujima in Japan’s Seto Inland Sea. Image credit: GIONImage credit: GIONThe new institution is Ando’s tenth project on the Benesse Art Site Naoshima across thirty years, his first being the Benesse House Museum in 1992. The first museum to bear the island’s name, the scheme is situated in a village setting and is designed to directly engage with the island’s traditional architectural language. Image credit: GIONImage credit: GIONThe museum features one above-ground and two subterranean levels, organized around a central skylit staircase that links the spaces vertically. Four galleries branch off from this core, providing a setting for a rotating collection of works by artists from Japan and across Asia. Image credit: Kenryou GuImage credit: Takeru KorodaBlending with its rural surroundings, the exterior employs local materials and finishes, including black plaster walls referencing Naoshima’s traditional burned-cedar facades and pebble walls inspired by vernacular architecture in the nearby Honmura district. The building’s sweeping roofline echoes the contours of the surrounding hills, designed to embed the structure into the landscape. Image credit: Takeru KorodaImage credit: GIONA cafe on the north side of the ground floor opens onto a terrace with panoramic views of the Seto Inland Sea, including sights of Teshima and local fishing boats. The public amenities are part of an effort to frame the museum as more than an exhibition space, but as a gathering place for locals and visitors. Image credit: GIONImage credit: Takeru Koroda“It is my belief that the experiences in Naoshima will forever linger in the memories of those who visit the island,” Ando said about the project. “The songs we listened to and the works of art we saw in our childhood are never forgotten. I hope that many children will visit Naoshima and be able to feel their senses being stimulated so that they can open up doors to a new world.” “Such “moving experiences” have the power to nourish human beings and refine our senses that will in turn lead to more opportunities to be emotionally moved,” Ando added. “Naoshima is an island like no other that is filled with such opportunities. For the Naoshima New Museum of Art, I once again endeavored to build a place that cultivates sensibilities and moves people’s hearts.”",
